## 1) Executive Summary
`slidegen` and `oai-skills/slides` are materially different by design. `slidegen` is a generator runtime that turns a typed `deckSpec` contract into branded deliverables (`.pptx` plus structured QA JSON) (`README.md:12`, `README.md:16`, `README.md:17`, `generator/index.js:303`, `generator/index.js:265`), while `slides` is an inspection/conversion toolkit centered on rasterization, montage creation, and overflow checks on existing files (`render_slides.py:143`, `render_slides.py:239`, `create_montage.py:57`, `slides_test.py:183`). This is a genuine contract split, not a superficial implementation difference.

Given your target state (SlideGen running as a ChatGPT skill where OAI skills are already embedded), the recommendation is to avoid duplicating generic `slides` functionality inside SlideGen. Specifically, do not re-implement `render_slides.py`/`create_montage.py`/`ensure_raster_image.py` behavior in SlideGen; call those capabilities as optional downstream steps from SlideGen output when preview or visual QA is needed (`render_slides.py:196`, `create_montage.py:195`, `ensure_raster_image.py:162`, `README.md:323`).

What SlideGen should adopt is integration, normalization, and policy. First, add an adapter layer that can invoke embedded `slides` capabilities after generation and attach results back into SlideGen’s existing QA envelope, so users still get one canonical report (`generator/index.js:265`, `generator/index.js:296`, `outputs/minimal-sample-oneqa/qa.json:3308`). Second, adopt the robust raster fallback flow from `slides` (PPTX->PDF with ODP fallback) for preview generation reliability rather than creating a new renderer branch (`render_slides.py:78`, `render_slides.py:103`). Third, use `slides_test.py`-style overflow checks as a complementary strict gate, especially since SlideGen’s current strict-overflow script is referenced but absent in this repo cut (`README.md:339`, `generator/index.js:165`, `slides_test.py:128`).

What SlideGen should not adopt is replacement of its core template-driven generation model. Do not swap out SlideGen’s schema validation, pagination logic, template package contract, or master/footer mapping with generic helper utilities from `slides`, because those capabilities are precisely where SlideGen carries product-specific value and brand correctness (`generator/runtime/render-deck.js:447`, `generator/runtime/paginate.js:257`, `generator/runtime/template-package.js:21`, `templates/kpmg-diligence/package/layouts.json:4646`). Also avoid pulling `slides` native-binary dependencies into the core generation path; keep them optional so generation remains deterministic and simpler to operate (`ensure_raster_image.py:8`, `ensure_raster_image.py:17`, `render_slides.py:86`).

The overall recommendation is a layered architecture: SlideGen remains the system of record for generation, template compliance, and machine-readable QA; embedded OAI `slides` capabilities are invoked as opt-in post-process services for preview and supplemental visual diagnostics; and results are merged back into one user-facing QA contract. This gives you reuse without duplication, keeps behavior consistent for agents/users, and preserves SlideGen’s differentiated responsibilities (`README.md:31`, `README.md:313`, `generator/runtime/render-deck.js:1040`, `pptxgenjs_helpers/index.js:13`).

